/* Frontend jargon & acronyms — clickable reference (FE-A11Y, auto-assembled) */
Object.assign(GLOSSARY_DATA, {
  "wcag": {"term":"WCAG","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["Web Content Accessibility Guidelines","WCAG 2.0","WCAG 2.1","WCAG 2.2","WCAG 2.x","WCAG 3"],"eli5":"A standardized set of testable rules that define what makes web content accessible to people with disabilities.","memory":"Web Content Accessibility Guidelines — the rulebook everyone grades accessibility against.","full":"<p><strong>WCAG</strong> (Web Content Accessibility Guidelines) is the internationally recognized standard for making web content accessible to people with disabilities. It is structured as a set of <em>success criteria</em> — concrete, testable statements — organized under four high-level principles (POUR: Perceivable, Operable, Understandable, Robust). Each success criterion is assigned a conformance level: <strong>A</strong> (minimum), <strong>AA</strong> (the de-facto target), or <strong>AAA</strong> (enhanced).</p><p>WCAG is published by the <strong>W3C</strong> (World Wide Web Consortium) through its <strong>Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI)</strong>. WCAG 1.0 was released in 1999. The far more influential WCAG 2.0 followed in 2008, restructured around the POUR principles and made technology-agnostic. WCAG 2.1 (2018) added criteria for mobile, low vision, and cognitive needs; WCAG 2.2 (2023) added more, including focus-appearance and dragging-movement criteria. The W3C is also developing <strong>WCAG 3</strong> (sometimes called Silver), a longer-term rework with a new scoring model, but it remains in draft as of 2026.</p><p>Its purpose is to give designers, developers, and lawmakers a single, objective yardstick for accessibility. It is still the backbone of the field because legislation and contracts worldwide point to it: the ADA case law in the US, Section 508, and the EU's EN 301 549 all effectively require <strong>WCAG 2.x level AA</strong>. Until WCAG 3 stabilizes, 2.x AA remains the practical and legal baseline.</p>","worked":"<p>WCAG 1.4.3 (Contrast, level AA) requires normal text to have at least a 4.5:1 contrast ratio against its background. This passes:</p><ul><li><code>color: #595959;</code> on <code>background: #ffffff;</code> &rarr; ratio &asymp; 7:1 ✓</li><li><code>color: #999999;</code> on <code>background: #ffffff;</code> &rarr; ratio &asymp; 2.8:1 ✗ (fails AA)</li></ul><p>And WCAG 2.4.3 (Focus Order) requires that tabbing through a page follows a logical sequence — for example, a modal's fields should receive focus in reading order, not jump around.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, WCAG is just <strong>a checklist of testable rules for \"can everyone actually use this?\"</strong> — turned into a formal standard so that designers, lawyers, and auditors all mean the same thing when they say a site is \"accessible.\"</p><p>The structure is a pyramid. At the top sit four <strong>principles</strong> (POUR). Under each principle are <strong>guidelines</strong> (broad goals). Under each guideline are <strong>success criteria</strong> — the actual pass/fail tests, like \"text has 4.5:1 contrast\" or \"every function works with a keyboard.\" Each criterion carries a level: <strong>A</strong> (you must), <strong>AA</strong> (you really should — and the law usually says you must), <strong>AAA</strong> (gold-plated, rarely required site-wide).</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of WCAG like a building code. The principles are \"the building must be safe and usable.\" The success criteria are the specific clauses: \"doorways at least 32 inches wide,\" \"ramps no steeper than 1:12.\" An inspector doesn't argue about philosophy — they measure against the clauses. Level AA is the code you must meet to get an occupancy permit; AAA is the luxury accessibility certification most buildings skip.</div><p>Why does this matter to a frontend developer? Because \"make it accessible\" is impossibly vague, but \"meet WCAG 2.2 AA\" is a finite, checkable list. It tells you exactly what to test: contrast ratios, keyboard operability, focus order, text alternatives, captions. Tools like axe and Lighthouse automate <em>some</em> of these checks, but many — is the alt text meaningful? does the reading order make sense? — still require a human reading against the criteria.</p><div class=\"key\">WCAG is the rulebook: four principles (POUR) &rarr; guidelines &rarr; testable success criteria graded A/AA/AAA. Published by the W3C's WAI, with 2.0 (2008), 2.1 (2018), and 2.2 (2023) as the live versions. \"AA\" is the number you'll be held to legally and contractually.</div>","related":["pour","aria","wai-ara","wai","a11y","ada","apca"]},
  "aria": {"term":"ARIA","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["Accessible Rich Internet Applications","WAI-ARIA"],"eli5":"A set of HTML attributes that tell assistive technology what a custom widget is and what state it's in, when native HTML can't say so.","memory":"Accessible Rich Internet Applications — bolt-on semantics for the rich, JS-driven UI that plain HTML didn't anticipate.","full":"<p><strong>ARIA</strong> (Accessible Rich Internet Applications), formally <strong>WAI-ARIA</strong>, is a W3C specification that defines a set of HTML attributes — <code>role</code>, plus <code>aria-*</code> states and properties — that describe the semantics of a UI element to assistive technologies like screen readers. Where native HTML elements (a <code>&lt;button&gt;</code>, a <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>, a checkbox) carry built-in role, name, and state for free, ARIA fills the gap for custom widgets built from generic <code>&lt;div&gt;</code>s and JavaScript.</p><p>WAI-ARIA was developed by the W3C's <strong>Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI)</strong>; version 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation in 2014, with 1.1 (2017) and 1.2 (2023) following as the web platform's component patterns matured. It was created precisely because the AJAX/single-page-app era produced dynamic, scripted controls — menus, tabs, sliders, live-updating regions — that the browser's native accessibility mapping had no vocabulary for.</p><p>Its purpose is to expose the right <em>role</em>, <em>name</em>, <em>state</em>, and <em>value</em> in the browser's accessibility tree so a screen reader can announce a custom control correctly. Crucially, ARIA <strong>changes only what is announced — it adds no behavior</strong>; you must still wire up keyboard handling and focus management yourself. The first rule of ARIA is \"don't use ARIA\" if a native element gives you the semantics and behavior for free. It remains essential today for genuinely custom widgets, but misuse (overriding a native role with a wrong ARIA role) actively harms users.</p>","worked":"<p>A custom toggle button built from a <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> has no native semantics, so ARIA supplies them:</p><ul><li><code>&lt;div role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\" aria-pressed=\"false\"&gt;Mute&lt;/div&gt;</code></li></ul><p>The <code>role=\"button\"</code> makes a screen reader announce it as a button; <code>aria-pressed</code> exposes the on/off state. But ARIA does nothing for behavior — you still need JS to handle <code>Enter</code>/<code>Space</code> and to flip <code>aria-pressed</code> to <code>\"true\"</code>. Better yet, just use <code>&lt;button aria-pressed=\"false\"&gt;Mute&lt;/button&gt;</code> and get the keyboard handling for free.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, ARIA is just <strong>a way to whisper extra meaning into the screen reader's ear</strong> when the HTML element itself can't. The browser builds an <em>accessibility tree</em> from your DOM — a parallel structure where each node exposes a <strong>role</strong> (what kind of thing am I?), a <strong>name</strong> (what am I called?), a <strong>state</strong> (am I checked? expanded? disabled?), and a <strong>value</strong>. Native elements populate that tree automatically. A bare <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> populates nothing useful. ARIA attributes let you fill those slots by hand.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Imagine a movie set. A real telephone prop is already obviously a telephone — that's a native <code>&lt;button&gt;</code>. But if you've built a \"phone\" out of a cardboard box, you tape a label on it that says \"PHONE — currently ringing\" so the camera (the screen reader) knows what it is and what it's doing. ARIA is that label. Here's the catch: the cardboard box still won't actually ring. The label describes; it doesn't function. You have to add the ringing — the keyboard handlers, the focus moves — yourself in JavaScript.</div><p>This is the single most-misunderstood thing about ARIA: <strong>ARIA changes what is read, not how it behaves.</strong> Slapping <code>role=\"button\"</code> on a div does not make <code>Enter</code> activate it. That's why the guidance is \"no ARIA is better than bad ARIA,\" and why rule one is: if a native element does the job, use the native element. <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> gives you the role, the name, the focusability, and the keyboard activation all at once.</p><div class=\"key\">ARIA = role + states/properties bolted onto markup to fix the accessibility tree for custom widgets. It informs assistive tech; it adds zero behavior. Prefer native HTML; reach for ARIA only when there's no native element that fits.</div>","related":["wai-ara","a11y","apg","wai","wcag"]},
  "wai-ara": {"term":"WAI-ARIA","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["WAI-ARIA","Accessible Rich Internet Applications (WAI-ARIA)","ARIA specification"],"eli5":"The formal W3C name for the ARIA specification — the full standard of roles, states, and properties for accessible rich UIs.","memory":"WAI (the initiative) + ARIA (the spec) = the official name of the accessibility-attributes standard.","full":"<p><strong>WAI-ARIA</strong> is the full, formal name of the <strong>ARIA</strong> specification: the \"WAI-\" prefix denotes that it is a product of the W3C's <strong>Web Accessibility Initiative</strong>. In everyday speech developers say \"ARIA,\" but the standards document, its companion authoring guidance, and citations use \"WAI-ARIA.\" It defines the complete taxonomy of <code>role</code> values (such as <code>menu</code>, <code>tablist</code>, <code>dialog</code>, <code>slider</code>) and the <code>aria-*</code> states and properties (such as <code>aria-expanded</code>, <code>aria-selected</code>, <code>aria-controls</code>).</p><p>The specification was created by the WAI and reached W3C Recommendation status as WAI-ARIA 1.0 in 2014, followed by 1.1 (2017) and 1.2 (2023). Alongside the core spec, the WAI publishes the <strong>ARIA Authoring Practices Guide (APG)</strong>, which shows how to assemble those roles and states into complete, keyboard-operable widget patterns (combobox, menu, tabs, treegrid, and so on).</p><p>Its purpose is to standardize the vocabulary browsers, assistive technologies, and developers all share, so that a <code>role=\"tab\"</code> means the same thing everywhere. It is still the authoritative reference whenever you build a component that native HTML doesn't cover — but, exactly as with ARIA, it specifies <em>semantics only</em>: the matching keyboard behavior (e.g. arrow-key navigation, roving tabindex) is something you implement, guided by the APG.</p>","worked":"<p>The WAI-ARIA tabs pattern uses a coordinated set of roles and states. A minimal tab list:</p><ul><li><code>&lt;div role=\"tablist\"&gt;</code></li><li><code>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;button role=\"tab\" aria-selected=\"true\" aria-controls=\"p1\" id=\"t1\"&gt;Account&lt;/button&gt;</code></li><li><code>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;button role=\"tab\" aria-selected=\"false\" aria-controls=\"p2\" id=\"t2\" tabindex=\"-1\"&gt;Billing&lt;/button&gt;</code></li><li><code>&lt;/div&gt;</code></li><li><code>&lt;div role=\"tabpanel\" id=\"p1\" aria-labelledby=\"t1\"&gt;…&lt;/div&gt;</code></li></ul><p>Per the APG, only the active tab has <code>tabindex=\"0\"</code> (roving tabindex), and arrow keys move selection — behavior you wire up in JS.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, WAI-ARIA is just <strong>ARIA's full legal name</strong> — the same set of <code>role</code> and <code>aria-*</code> attributes, but spelled out the way the standards body refers to it. The \"WAI-\" reminds you who owns it: the W3C's Web Accessibility Initiative. When someone writes \"per WAI-ARIA\" or cites \"the WAI-ARIA APG,\" they are pointing at the authoritative spec and its pattern cookbook, not a different technology.</p><div class=\"analogy\">It's like \"H₂O\" versus \"water.\" In the lab report you write H₂O; at the dinner table you ask for water. \"WAI-ARIA\" is the lab-report name that shows up in specs and audit reports; \"ARIA\" is what you say at your standup. Same molecule.</div><p>What the formal spec adds beyond the casual name is the <strong>complete catalog</strong>: every valid role, which states each role supports, and which roles can be nested in which. The companion <strong>APG</strong> (Authoring Practices Guide) then turns that catalog into recipes — \"here is exactly how to build a conforming menu, including the keyboard model.\" That keyboard model is where the famous <em>roving tabindex</em> lives: in a composite widget like a menu or toolbar, exactly one child has <code>tabindex=\"0\"</code> and the rest have <code>tabindex=\"-1\"</code>, so Tab enters the group once and arrow keys move <em>within</em> it.</p><p>The reason to know the full name is mostly literacy: WCAG references it, screen-reader bug reports reference it, and the APG patterns reference it. When you see \"WAI-ARIA,\" read it as \"the official ARIA standard plus the W3C's blessed how-to.\"</p><div class=\"key\">WAI-ARIA = the formal W3C name for ARIA (WAI = the initiative that publishes it). Same roles/states/properties you call \"ARIA,\" plus the APG, which supplies the complete widget patterns — including keyboard behavior like roving tabindex — that ARIA's semantics alone don't provide.</div>","related":["aria","apg","wai","a11y","wcag"]},
  "wai": {"term":"WAI","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["Web Accessibility Initiative","W3C WAI"],"eli5":"The group within the W3C that produces the web's accessibility standards, including WCAG and WAI-ARIA.","memory":"Web Accessibility Initiative — the W3C's accessibility department; it's the WAI in WAI-ARIA.","full":"<p><strong>WAI</strong> (Web Accessibility Initiative) is the part of the <strong>W3C</strong> (World Wide Web Consortium) responsible for the web's accessibility work. It coordinates the working groups and produces the standards, guidelines, and supporting materials that define how to make web content and applications usable by people with disabilities. Its best-known outputs are <strong>WCAG</strong> (the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines) and <strong>WAI-ARIA</strong> (the Accessible Rich Internet Applications spec), along with the ARIA Authoring Practices Guide (APG) and numerous tutorials and evaluation resources.</p><p>The WAI was launched by the W3C in the late 1990s, around the same era as WCAG 1.0 (1999), to give accessibility a dedicated, ongoing home within the standards process rather than treating it as an afterthought. Since then it has shepherded every major WCAG revision (2.0, 2.1, 2.2) and the ARIA family of specifications.</p><p>Its purpose is to set and maintain consensus standards so that browsers, assistive-technology vendors, authors, and regulators all build to the same target. It remains the authoritative body for web accessibility today — when legislation references \"WCAG\" or a spec is cited as \"WAI-ARIA,\" the \"WAI\" is naming exactly this initiative as the source of truth.</p>","worked":"<p>You encounter the WAI mostly as the <em>publisher</em> behind the standards you cite. For example, an accessibility statement might read:</p><ul><li>\"This site conforms to <strong>WCAG 2.2 level AA</strong>, published by the W3C <strong>Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI)</strong>.\"</li></ul><p>And the \"WAI-\" prefix on <code>WAI-ARIA</code> is a direct attribution: the ARIA spec is a WAI product. The WAI also hosts the ARIA APG, the reference for patterns like roving tabindex.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, the WAI is just <strong>the accessibility team inside the organization that runs the web's standards</strong>. The W3C is the body that standardizes HTML, CSS, and the rest of the platform; the WAI is its dedicated branch for \"make sure all of this works for people with disabilities.\"</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of the W3C as a city government and the WAI as its accessibility-and-building-access department. The department doesn't pave every road itself, but it writes the access codes (WCAG), the standard fixtures catalog (WAI-ARIA), and the how-to manuals (the APG) that everyone else — browser makers, developers, auditors — must follow.</div><p>Why does the name keep showing up? Because attribution matters in standards. When a law says you must meet \"WCAG AA,\" it is relying on a document the WAI authored and maintains. When you write <code>role=\"dialog\"</code>, you're using a vocabulary the WAI defined in WAI-ARIA — the \"WAI-\" literally credits the initiative. And when you look up how to build an accessible combobox, the canonical recipe lives in the WAI's APG.</p><p>For a working developer, the practical takeaway is trust and traceability: WAI publications are the <em>authoritative</em> source. If a blog post and the WAI spec disagree, the WAI spec wins. Knowing that the WAI sits under the W3C also helps you find primary documentation instead of secondhand summaries — and primary docs are where the exact, correct details (conformance levels, valid roles, required states) live.</p><div class=\"key\">WAI = Web Accessibility Initiative, the W3C's accessibility branch. It's the publisher of WCAG and WAI-ARIA (the \"WAI-\" is its signature) and the home of the APG. When you need the authoritative answer on web accessibility, the WAI is the source.</div>","related":["wcag","aria","wai-ara","apg","a11y"]},
  "a11y": {"term":"a11y","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["accessibility","a11y (accessibility)"],"eli5":"A numeronym shorthand for the word \"accessibility\" — designing software so people with disabilities can use it.","memory":"a + 11 letters + y = \"accessibility\" — the 11 stands for the letters between the a and the y.","full":"<p><strong>a11y</strong> is the conventional shorthand for <strong>accessibility</strong>: the practice of building websites and applications that people with disabilities — visual, motor, auditory, cognitive — can perceive, operate, and understand. The form is a <em>numeronym</em>: take \"accessibility,\" keep the first letter <code>a</code> and the last letter <code>y</code>, and replace the 11 letters in between with the number 11. (The same pattern gives \"i18n\" for internationalization and \"l10n\" for localization.)</p><p>The numeronym style dates back to internet/email culture and became standard in web development as accessibility grew into a first-class concern, popularized through hashtags, tooling names, and community resources. It's a label, not a standard — the actual rules live in WCAG and the actual semantics in ARIA — but it's the word the whole field uses to refer to itself.</p><p>Its purpose is purely linguistic convenience: \"a11y\" is fast to type and tag. It remains ubiquitous today in tooling (linters, test libraries), team vocabulary (\"the a11y tree,\" \"a11y review\"), and documentation. When you read about the browser building \"the a11y tree from the DOM + CSS,\" it simply means the <em>accessibility</em> tree.</p>","worked":"<p>\"a11y\" appears wherever accessibility does, just abbreviated:</p><ul><li><strong>The a11y tree</strong>: the browser builds the accessibility tree from the DOM + CSS — a parallel structure of nodes, each exposing <code>role</code>, <code>name</code>, <code>state</code>, and <code>value</code> — and hands it to platform accessibility APIs (UIA on Windows, IAccessible2, AX on macOS).</li><li>A pull-request label like <code>a11y</code> tags accessibility-related changes.</li><li>An <code>eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y</code> lint rule flags markup that screen readers can't use.</li></ul>","teach":"<p>At its core, a11y is just <strong>a typing shortcut for the word \"accessibility.\"</strong> There's no hidden technology behind it — it's the same concept, written the same way developers write \"i18n\" for internationalization. The trick is a <em>numeronym</em>: keep the first and last letters, count the letters in between, and stick that number in the middle. <code>a</code> + (11 letters: c-c-e-s-s-i-b-i-l-i-t) + <code>y</code> = <strong>a11y</strong>.</p><div class=\"analogy\">It's like a license-plate abbreviation. \"GR8\" isn't a different word from \"great\" — it's the same word, squeezed to fit. \"a11y\" is \"accessibility\" squeezed to fit a hashtag, a file name, or a Jira label. Once you know the decoder ring (first letter, count, last letter), you can read i18n (internationalization), l10n (localization), and a11y on sight.</div><p>Where it gets interesting is the one place beginners genuinely misread it: <strong>the \"a11y tree.\"</strong> That's not a special kind of tree — it's the <em>accessibility tree</em>, the parallel model the browser derives from your DOM and CSS so assistive technologies can introspect the page. Each node in it reports a role, a name, a state, and a value, and the browser feeds that tree to the operating system's accessibility APIs, which screen readers like NVDA, JAWS, and VoiceOver read from.</p><p>So when you see a11y, mentally expand it to \"accessibility\" and the sentence becomes plain. The shorthand also signals culture: a team that says \"a11y review\" and ships an <code>a11y</code> lint plugin is a team that treats inclusive design as routine engineering, not an afterthought.</p><div class=\"key\">a11y = \"accessibility\" written as a numeronym (a + 11 letters + y). Same family as i18n and l10n. The most important place to recognize it is \"a11y tree\" = the accessibility tree the browser builds from DOM + CSS for assistive technology.</div>","related":["wcag","aria","wai","nvda","jaws","apg"]},
  "ada": {"term":"ADA","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["Americans with Disabilities Act","ADA Title III"],"eli5":"A US civil-rights law banning disability discrimination, which courts have applied to websites — making WCAG conformance a legal concern.","memory":"Americans with Disabilities Act — the US law that turns web accessibility from \"nice to have\" into legal risk.","full":"<p><strong>ADA</strong> (Americans with Disabilities Act) is a United States federal civil-rights law that prohibits discrimination against people with disabilities. It was signed into law in <strong>1990</strong> and significantly amended in 2008. Although it predates the modern web, US courts have increasingly interpreted its public-accommodations provisions (notably <strong>Title III</strong>) to cover websites and mobile apps, which is why the ADA matters to frontend developers even though the statute itself doesn't mention HTML.</p><p>The ADA does not name a technical standard, but in practice litigation and settlements have coalesced around <strong>WCAG level AA</strong> as the benchmark courts and parties use to judge whether a site is accessible. This sits alongside other US requirements like <strong>Section 508</strong> (which governs federal agencies and explicitly incorporates WCAG) and, internationally, the EU's <strong>EN 301 549</strong>. Together these are why \"AA\" is treated as the de-facto legal and contractual target.</p><p>Its purpose is broad equal access to goods, services, and public life for people with disabilities; its web relevance is that non-compliant sites face real legal exposure (demand letters and lawsuits are common). It remains a primary driver of accessibility budgets and a major reason organizations commit to WCAG conformance today.</p>","worked":"<p>The ADA itself sets no code-level rule, but its case law makes WCAG conformance the practical defense. In an accessibility audit you'll see reasoning like:</p><ul><li>\"Color contrast on the checkout button is 3.1:1, below WCAG 2.2 AA's 4.5:1 — an <strong>ADA</strong> risk for a public-facing e-commerce flow.\"</li><li>\"Keyboard-only users can't complete the form (fails WCAG 2.1.1) — a likely <strong>ADA Title III</strong> exposure.\"</li></ul><p>So while you never write code \"to the ADA,\" you write it to WCAG AA <em>because of</em> the ADA.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, the ADA is just <strong>a US anti-discrimination law that courts have stretched to cover the web</strong> — which is what turns accessibility from a moral nice-to-have into a legal must-do for American businesses. As a developer you'll rarely read the statute, but you'll constantly feel its gravity: it's the reason \"we should be accessible\" becomes \"we need to meet WCAG AA by the deadline.\"</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of the ADA like a building's wheelchair-ramp requirement. The law says \"public places must be accessible\"; it does <em>not</em> specify the exact ramp slope — that detail lives in a separate technical code. On the web, the ADA is the \"must be accessible\" law, and <strong>WCAG AA</strong> is the technical code everyone has agreed counts as \"accessible enough.\" Build the ramp to code and you're defensible; ignore it and you invite a complaint.</div><p>Two things make this concrete for frontend work. First, the ADA names <em>no</em> technical standard itself — the WCAG-AA benchmark comes from years of US lawsuits and settlements converging on it. Second, the ADA isn't alone: <strong>Section 508</strong> binds federal agencies and bakes WCAG in directly, and the EU's <strong>EN 301 549</strong> plays a parallel role abroad. That global stack is why audit reports treat AA, not A and not AAA, as the line.</p><p>Practically, the ADA is the answer to \"why does the contrast ratio actually matter to the business?\" A failing checkout button isn't just a usability gripe — for a public-facing US site it's potential legal exposure. Knowing the ADA exists helps you frame accessibility work to stakeholders in terms they fund: risk, not just righteousness.</p><div class=\"key\">ADA = Americans with Disabilities Act (1990), a US civil-rights law courts apply to websites. It specifies no code, but case law makes WCAG level AA the practical target — alongside Section 508 (US federal) and EN 301 549 (EU). It's the legal \"why\" behind meeting AA.</div>","related":["wcag","pour","a11y","wai"]},
  "nvda": {"term":"NVDA","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["NonVisual Desktop Access","Non-Visual Desktop Access"],"eli5":"A free, open-source screen reader for Windows that reads on-screen content aloud for blind and low-vision users.","memory":"NonVisual Desktop Access — the free Windows screen reader devs test with first.","full":"<p><strong>NVDA</strong> (NonVisual Desktop Access) is a free, open-source <strong>screen reader</strong> for the Windows operating system. A screen reader converts on-screen content — text, controls, structure — into synthesized speech (or refreshable Braille), letting blind and low-vision users perceive and operate software and the web without a visual display. NVDA reads from the browser's accessibility tree, announcing each element's role, name, and state.</p><p>NVDA was created by <strong>NV Access</strong>, a non-profit founded by two blind developers in Australia, with the project beginning in the mid-2000s. Being free and open-source was a deliberate mission: commercial screen readers were expensive, and NVDA dramatically lowered the cost barrier for blind users worldwide. It receives ongoing updates and has become one of the most widely used screen readers globally.</p><p>Its purpose is to give blind users full, affordable access to Windows and the web; for developers, it's also a primary <em>testing</em> tool. NVDA is commonly paired with Firefox or Chrome. It remains heavily used today both because it's free and because it's the practical companion to <strong>JAWS</strong> (the paid enterprise default) when verifying that custom widgets, focus management, and live regions actually announce correctly — things automated checkers can't judge.</p>","worked":"<p>To verify accessibility, a developer runs NVDA and tabs through the UI, listening to what's announced:</p><ul><li>A correct button announces: <em>\"Mute, button\"</em> — role and name present.</li><li>A bare <code>&lt;div onclick&gt;</code> announces nothing useful — NVDA exposes no role, revealing the bug.</li><li>An <code>aria-live</code> region: NVDA should speak the new text when it updates; if it stays silent, the live region isn't wired correctly.</li></ul><p>NVDA pairs naturally with Firefox or Chrome for this kind of manual screen-reader testing.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, NVDA is just <strong>a program that speaks your screen out loud</strong> so someone who can't see it can still use the computer. It is the most common <em>free</em> example of a screen reader, and on Windows it's usually the first tool developers reach for to hear what their site actually sounds like to a blind user.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Imagine someone reading a webpage to you over the phone, but a very literal someone: they announce not just the words but the structure — \"heading level 2: Pricing,\" \"link: Buy now,\" \"checkbox, not checked.\" That narrator is NVDA. And here's the catch — it can only narrate what's actually labeled. If you handed them a page where a button is secretly a blank box, they'd say \"clickable\" or nothing at all, and the listener would be stuck. That gap is exactly the accessibility bug you're hunting for.</div><p>NVDA reads from the <em>accessibility tree</em> the browser builds, so it surfaces the same role/name/state data that ARIA populates. This is why screen-reader testing catches things automated tools can't: a linter can confirm an <code>alt</code> attribute <em>exists</em>, but only listening with NVDA tells you whether the alt text is <em>meaningful</em>, whether the reading order makes sense, whether focus moves sanely through a modal, and whether a live region actually announces.</p><p>Practically, NVDA sits at the top of the screen-reader landscape alongside a few others you should recognize: <strong>JAWS</strong> (paid, the enterprise default on Windows), <strong>VoiceOver</strong> (built into macOS and iOS, pairs with Safari), <strong>TalkBack</strong> (Android), and Narrator (Windows built-in). NVDA's superpower is that it's free and open-source, so there's zero excuse not to install it and test.</p><div class=\"key\">NVDA = NonVisual Desktop Access, a free open-source Windows screen reader from NV Access. It speaks the accessibility tree aloud, pairs well with Firefox/Chrome, and is the go-to manual-testing tool for checking whether your roles, labels, focus order, and live regions actually work — the human-judgment things automation misses.</div>","related":["jaws","a11y","aria","wcag","apg"]},
  "jaws": {"term":"JAWS","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["Job Access With Speech"],"eli5":"A long-established commercial screen reader for Windows, widely used in enterprise and government settings.","memory":"Job Access With Speech — the paid, enterprise-default Windows screen reader.","full":"<p><strong>JAWS</strong> (Job Access With Speech) is a commercial <strong>screen reader</strong> for Windows. Like other screen readers, it converts on-screen content into synthesized speech and Braille output, reading the browser's accessibility tree so blind and low-vision users can navigate and operate applications and the web. JAWS is known for a deep feature set, extensive scripting capabilities, and strong support in professional and enterprise environments.</p><p>JAWS is developed by <strong>Freedom Scientific</strong> (now part of Vispero) and is one of the oldest and most established screen readers, with roots going back to the DOS era and a long history on Windows. Because it has been the dominant assistive technology in workplaces and government for decades, it became — and remains — the <em>enterprise default</em> on Windows.</p><p>Its purpose is full nonvisual access to Windows software and the web, particularly in settings where its maturity and support contracts matter. It is paid (often via subscription or license), which is the main contrast with the free, open-source <strong>NVDA</strong>. Developers frequently test against both: JAWS because it's what many real users in regulated industries rely on, NVDA because it's free and widely used. JAWS remains in heavy use today despite the rise of free alternatives, largely due to entrenched enterprise adoption.</p>","worked":"<p>Because JAWS dominates enterprise, accessibility test plans often require it explicitly:</p><ul><li>\"Verify the data grid is operable with <strong>JAWS</strong> + Chrome: arrow keys move between cells, and each cell's header is announced.\"</li><li>\"Confirm form errors are read by both <strong>JAWS</strong> and NVDA via the <code>aria-live=\"assertive\"</code> region.\"</li></ul><p>Subtle behavior differences between JAWS and NVDA (e.g. how each handles a given ARIA pattern) are exactly why teams test on more than one screen reader.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, JAWS is just <strong>another screen reader</strong> — same job as NVDA (speak the screen for blind users) — but it's the <em>paid, enterprise-grade</em> one with a very long history. If NVDA is the free tool everyone can grab, JAWS is the established standard that large organizations, governments, and regulated industries have standardized on for years.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of screen readers like web browsers. NVDA and JAWS are two different \"browsers\" for blind users — they both render the same accessibility tree, but each has its own quirks in <em>how</em> it interprets and voices things. Just as a layout can look fine in Chrome but break in Safari, an ARIA widget can announce perfectly in NVDA yet behave oddly in JAWS. That's why you test in more than one, the same way you test cross-browser.</div><p>Knowing JAWS exists matters for two practical reasons. First, <strong>audience</strong>: if your users are in a corporate, financial, or government setting, a large share of them are likely on JAWS, so \"it works in NVDA\" isn't a complete answer. Second, <strong>fidelity</strong>: JAWS and NVDA don't always agree on the exact same markup. A complex custom widget — a tree grid, a combobox built per the APG — can expose differences in how each tool handles roving tabindex, live regions, or naming. Catching those differences is the whole point of testing across multiple screen readers.</p><p>The screen-reader lineup to keep straight: <strong>JAWS</strong> (paid, Windows, enterprise default), <strong>NVDA</strong> (free, Windows, open-source), <strong>VoiceOver</strong> (macOS/iOS, built-in), <strong>TalkBack</strong> (Android), Narrator (Windows built-in). For Windows web testing, JAWS and NVDA are the two you'll hear named most.</p><div class=\"key\">JAWS = Job Access With Speech, a long-standing commercial Windows screen reader from Freedom Scientific/Vispero. It's the paid enterprise default, contrasted with free open-source NVDA. Test on both — they interpret the same ARIA differently, like cross-browser testing for assistive tech.</div>","related":["nvda","a11y","aria","wcag","apg"]},
  "apg": {"term":"APG","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["ARIA Authoring Practices Guide","WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide","WAI-ARIA APG","ARIA Authoring Practices"],"eli5":"A W3C guide of ready-made, keyboard-complete recipes for building common accessible UI widgets with ARIA.","memory":"ARIA Authoring Practices Guide — the official cookbook of accessible widget patterns (menus, tabs, comboboxes).","full":"<p><strong>APG</strong> (ARIA Authoring Practices Guide), often cited as the <strong>WAI-ARIA APG</strong>, is a W3C resource that shows developers how to build accessible UI components using ARIA roles, states, and properties — combined with the keyboard interaction each pattern requires. Where the ARIA specification defines the <em>vocabulary</em> (what roles and states exist), the APG provides the <em>recipes</em>: complete patterns for widgets like menus, tabs, comboboxes, dialogs, accordions, sliders, and tree grids.</p><p>The APG is published by the W3C's <strong>Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI)</strong>, the same group behind WAI-ARIA itself, and has evolved alongside the ARIA spec versions. Each pattern documents the required roles and states <em>and</em> the expected keyboard behavior — for example, the menu and toolbar patterns specify <strong>roving tabindex</strong>: exactly one child has <code>tabindex=\"0\"</code> (the active item) while all others have <code>tabindex=\"-1\"</code>, so Tab enters the group once and arrow keys move within it.</p><p>Its purpose is to close ARIA's biggest gap: ARIA supplies semantics but <em>no behavior</em>, so developers routinely got the keyboard model wrong. The APG gives a canonical, tested blueprint. It remains the go-to reference today whenever you build a custom widget that native HTML doesn't provide — and it's exactly what a \"custom dropdown missing arrow-key roving tabindex\" is failing to follow.</p>","worked":"<p>The APG's roving tabindex pattern, applied to a custom menu:</p><ul><li><code>&lt;ul role=\"menu\"&gt;</code></li><li><code>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li role=\"menuitem\" tabindex=\"0\"&gt;Cut&lt;/li&gt;</code> &larr; active item, the only one in the tab order</li><li><code>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li role=\"menuitem\" tabindex=\"-1\"&gt;Copy&lt;/li&gt;</code></li><li><code>&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li role=\"menuitem\" tabindex=\"-1\"&gt;Paste&lt;/li&gt;</code></li><li><code>&lt;/ul&gt;</code></li></ul><p>Per the APG, <code>ArrowDown</code>/<code>ArrowUp</code> move the active item: shift <code>tabindex=\"0\"</code> to the newly focused item, set the old one to <code>-1</code>, and call <code>.focus()</code>. A dropdown lacking this is the classic APG-violation bug.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, the APG is just <strong>a cookbook of ready-made accessible widgets.</strong> ARIA gives you ingredients — roles like <code>menu</code> and states like <code>aria-expanded</code> — but it pointedly does <em>not</em> tell you how to cook them into a working control, and it adds no keyboard behavior at all. Developers kept getting that part wrong. The APG is the W3C's answer: here is the exact, tested recipe for each common widget, semantics <em>and</em> keyboard model included.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of ARIA as a pantry full of labeled ingredients and the APG as the recipe book. Anyone can own flour, eggs, and sugar (roles and states), but that doesn't mean they can make a soufflé. The APG hands you the step-by-step: which ingredients, in what order, and — critically — the technique (the keyboard interactions) that makes it actually rise instead of collapse.</div><p>The single most important technique the APG teaches is <strong>roving tabindex</strong>, used in composite widgets like menus, toolbars, and tab lists. The idea: a group should be <em>one</em> stop in the Tab order, not twenty. So exactly one child carries <code>tabindex=\"0\"</code> (the currently active item) and every other child carries <code>tabindex=\"-1\"</code> (focusable by script, but skipped by Tab). Tab moves you <em>into</em> the group once; then the <em>arrow keys</em> move focus <em>within</em> it, and your JS \"roves\" the <code>0</code> from item to item as the user navigates.</p><p>Why rely on the APG instead of improvising? Because these patterns are the consensus, screen-reader-tested blueprints. A custom dropdown that you can Tab into but not arrow-navigate is the textbook APG violation — it has the ARIA roles but skipped the keyboard recipe. Following the APG means your widget behaves the way assistive-tech users expect, the way the native equivalent would.</p><div class=\"key\">APG = (WAI-)ARIA Authoring Practices Guide, the W3C/WAI cookbook of accessible widget patterns. It fills ARIA's gap by specifying both semantics and keyboard behavior — most famously roving tabindex (one child <code>tabindex=\"0\"</code>, the rest <code>-1</code>, arrow keys move focus). Reach for it whenever you build a control HTML doesn't natively provide.</div>","related":["aria","wai-ara","wai","a11y","wcag"]},
  "apca": {"term":"APCA","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["Accessible Perceptual Contrast Algorithm","Advanced Perceptual Contrast Algorithm"],"eli5":"A newer, perception-based way to measure text/background contrast that accounts for which color is lighter — a candidate to replace WCAG's older ratio method.","memory":"Accessible Perceptual Contrast Algorithm — perceptual and polarity-aware, the proposed successor to the 4.5:1 ratio.","full":"<p><strong>APCA</strong> (Accessible Perceptual Contrast Algorithm) is a contrast-measurement method designed to model how humans actually <em>perceive</em> the contrast between text and its background. Unlike the older WCAG 2.x approach — a simple luminance <em>ratio</em> with a fixed 4.5:1 (normal text) / 3:1 (large text) AA threshold — APCA is <strong>perceptual</strong> and <strong>polarity-aware</strong>: it distinguishes light-text-on-dark from dark-text-on-light, and weights its scores according to how the eye responds to those situations, font weight, and size.</p><p>APCA was developed as part of the research feeding into <strong>WCAG 3</strong>, the W3C's next-generation accessibility guidelines, which remain in draft as of 2026. It produces a contrast score (commonly described on a roughly 0–100+ \"Lc\" scale) rather than a single ratio, and pairs that score with lookup guidance based on text size and weight, rather than one universal threshold.</p><p>Its purpose is to fix known shortcomings of the 2.x ratio — which can pass some color pairs that look poor and fail others that read fine, and which ignores polarity. WCAG 3 is <em>exploring</em> APCA as a future replacement, but it is not yet a ratified requirement. As of 2026, the legally and contractually binding standard is still <strong>WCAG 2.x AA's luminance ratio</strong> (4.5:1 / 3:1); APCA is best treated as a forward-looking, advisory tool today.</p>","worked":"<p>The two methods can disagree, which is the whole motivation for APCA:</p><ul><li><strong>WCAG 2.x:</strong> computes a single ratio, e.g. <code>#777</code> on <code>#fff</code> &rarr; ~4.48:1 — just <em>fails</em> AA's 4.5:1, regardless of whether text is on light or dark.</li><li><strong>APCA:</strong> returns a polarity-aware <code>Lc</code> score and tells you the score needed <em>for that specific font size and weight</em> — so a thin 14px label demands more contrast than a bold 24px heading.</li></ul><p>Practical stance in 2026: ship to WCAG 2.x AA for compliance, optionally use APCA as a sanity check on real-world legibility.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, APCA is just <strong>a smarter ruler for measuring whether text is readable against its background.</strong> The old WCAG 2.x ruler computes a plain <em>ratio</em> of luminances and checks it against one number (4.5:1). It's simple, but it has a blind spot: human vision doesn't respond linearly to light, and it treats \"dark text on light\" and \"light text on dark\" as if they were the same — they aren't.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Imagine judging how loud a sound is by measuring raw air-pressure numbers, ignoring that the human ear is far more sensitive to some frequencies than others. You'd flag some \"loud\" sounds nobody can hear and miss some quiet ones that are piercing. That's the WCAG 2.x ratio: mathematically tidy, but not tuned to the eye. APCA is like switching to a perceptual loudness scale (decibels weighted for human hearing) — it's built around how people <em>actually perceive</em>, factoring in polarity (light-on-dark vs dark-on-light), plus font size and weight.</div><p>Concretely, APCA gives you a perceptual <em>lightness-contrast</em> score (often shown as <code>Lc</code>) and then says \"for 14px regular weight you need this much; for 24px bold you can get away with less\" — context-sensitive, where 2.x had one flat threshold. That better matches reality: a thin, tiny label genuinely needs more contrast than a big bold headline.</p><p>The crucial caveat for 2026: APCA is the <em>future-leaning</em> method being explored for <strong>WCAG 3</strong>, but WCAG 3 isn't ratified, and the standard you're legally and contractually held to is still WCAG 2.x AA's luminance ratio. So: design and audit to the 2.x ratio for compliance, and treat APCA as a more accurate second opinion on legibility — not yet as the rule.</p><div class=\"key\">APCA = Accessible Perceptual Contrast Algorithm: perceptual, polarity-aware contrast scoring tied to font size/weight, developed for the still-draft WCAG 3. It aims to replace WCAG 2.x's flat luminance ratio — but as of 2026, the binding requirement remains 2.x AA's 4.5:1 / 3:1.</div>","related":["wcag","pour","a11y","ada"]},
  "uia": {"term":"UIA","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["UI Automation","Microsoft UI Automation","UIAutomation"],"eli5":"UIA (UI Automation) is the Windows operating-system accessibility API that screen readers and other assistive tech use to read and control on-screen UI, including the browser's accessibility tree.","memory":"UIA = User Interface Automation — the Windows 'automation' layer that lets a screen reader drive the UI.","full":"<p><strong>What it is.</strong> UI Automation (UIA) is Microsoft's platform-level accessibility framework on Windows. It defines a tree of <em>automation elements</em>, each exposing a <code>ControlType</code> (role), a <code>Name</code>, states, values, and a set of <em>control patterns</em> (e.g. Invoke, Toggle, Value, Selection). Browsers map their internal accessibility tree — itself computed from the DOM plus CSS — onto UIA so that assistive technologies (screen readers like Narrator, NVDA, JAWS), test automation, and other tools can read and operate the page without touching pixels.</p><p><strong>History / origin.</strong> UIA was created by Microsoft and shipped with the .NET Framework 3.0 / Windows Presentation Foundation era in the mid-2000s, as the successor to the older <em>Microsoft Active Accessibility</em> (MSAA / IAccessible) API from the late 1990s. It was later standardized and broadened, and a provider/client model lets any app expose or consume the tree. On the web, browser engines bridge their accessibility tree to UIA on Windows (and to IAccessible2, ATK/AT-SPI on Linux, and NSAccessibility on macOS).</p><p><strong>Purpose & why still used.</strong> UIA exists so that assistive tech can present a semantic model of the UI — role, name, state, value — to users who cannot see or use a pointer, and so automated tests can drive real controls. It remains the primary Windows accessibility API today: every modern browser surfaces its accessibility tree through UIA on Windows, which is exactly why correct HTML semantics and ARIA matter — they feed the tree that UIA exposes.</p>","worked":"<p>This native control has an implicit role and name that the browser maps into the accessibility tree and exposes to UIA as <code>ControlType=Button</code>, <code>Name=\"Save\"</code>:</p><ul><li><code>&lt;button&gt;Save&lt;/button&gt;</code> → UIA element: role <em>Button</em>, name <em>Save</em>, supports the <em>Invoke</em> pattern.</li><li><code>&lt;input type=\"checkbox\" aria-label=\"Remember me\"&gt;</code> → UIA element: role <em>CheckBox</em>, name <em>Remember me</em>, supports the <em>Toggle</em> pattern with state on/off.</li></ul><p>A screen reader queries UIA, reads \"Save, button,\" and when the user activates it, calls the Invoke pattern — never needing the visual rendering.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, UIA is just a <strong>second, machine-readable copy of your UI that screen readers can read</strong>. Your visual interface is made of pixels a sighted person interprets; UIA is a parallel tree of objects — each one says \"I am a button named Save, and I can be invoked\" — that software can interpret instead.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Think of a museum. The paintings on the wall are the pixels — beautiful, but useless to someone who can't see them. UIA is the audio guide: a separate, structured description of every exhibit (\"to your left, a portrait, oil on canvas, you may press play to hear more\") that lets a blind visitor experience the same museum through a different channel.</div><p>Here's the chain. You write HTML. The browser parses it into the DOM, applies CSS, and from that computes an <strong>accessibility tree</strong> — one node per meaningful element, each carrying a <em>role</em> (button, heading, checkbox), a <em>name</em> (its accessible label), a <em>state</em> (checked, disabled, expanded), and sometimes a <em>value</em>. On Windows, the browser then exposes that tree through UIA. A screen reader is a UIA <em>client</em>: it walks the tree, speaks each node, and sends actions back (\"invoke this button\").</p><p>Why should you, a web developer, care about a Windows API you never call directly? Because <strong>the quality of the UIA tree is decided by your markup</strong>. A <code>&lt;div onclick&gt;</code> styled to look like a button exposes role <em>generic</em> with no name and no invoke pattern — invisible to UIA, invisible to the screen reader. A real <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> exposes everything for free. This is the whole reason \"use semantic HTML\" and \"add ARIA only when HTML can't express it\" are accessibility gospel: they're instructions for building a good tree.</p><div class=\"key\">UIA is the Windows pipe through which your accessibility tree reaches screen readers. You never call it, but every semantic choice you make in HTML and ARIA is ultimately a message written to UIA. Good semantics in, usable UIA tree out.</div>","related":["accname"]},
  "accname": {"term":"accname","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["Accessible Name and Description Computation","accname spec","accname-aam"],"eli5":"accname is the W3C algorithm that determines the single text string a screen reader announces as an element's 'accessible name', resolved from a strict precedence of sources like aria-labelledby, aria-label, and native labels.","memory":"accname = the ACCessible NAME computation — the rulebook for what name a screen reader speaks.","full":"<p><strong>What it is.</strong> <em>Accessible Name and Description Computation</em> (accname) is a W3C specification that defines the precise, ordered algorithm a browser uses to compute the <em>accessible name</em> (and accessible description) of an element. The accessible name is the short label assistive tech announces — e.g. \"Search, button.\" Because many sources can supply a name (ARIA attributes, native labels, text content, attributes like <code>title</code>), accname specifies their priority so every browser resolves the same name from the same markup.</p><p><strong>History / origin.</strong> accname is published by the W3C (developed within the work on ARIA and the accessibility APIs). It accompanies the ARIA specifications and the Accessibility API Mappings, and has evolved alongside them (the \"1.1\" / \"1.2\"-generation specs) to keep name and description computation consistent across the WAI-ARIA family. It is the normative companion that browsers implement so that <code>aria-labelledby</code>, <code>aria-label</code>, and host-language labels behave identically everywhere.</p><p><strong>Purpose & why still used.</strong> Its purpose is determinism: without a single agreed precedence, the same button could be announced differently in different browsers/screen readers. accname is still the live, authoritative source for name resolution — it is what the accessibility tree (and therefore UIA / platform APIs) relies on to populate the <code>name</code> field of every node. Any developer debugging \"why does the screen reader say the wrong thing?\" is debugging accname precedence.</p>","worked":"<p>accname resolves the name in this order (first non-empty wins):</p><ul><li><code>aria-labelledby</code> (collect text of referenced elements) — highest</li><li><code>aria-label</code></li><li>host-language labeling — <code>&lt;label for&gt;</code>, <code>img[alt]</code>, <code>&lt;legend&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;caption&gt;</code></li><li>the element's own text content</li><li><code>title</code> attribute — last-resort fallback</li></ul><p>Examples:</p><ul><li><code>&lt;button aria-label=\"Close\"&gt;X&lt;/button&gt;</code> → name is \"Close\" (aria-label beats text content \"X\").</li><li><code>&lt;span id=\"t\"&gt;Delete&lt;/span&gt;&lt;button aria-labelledby=\"t\"&gt;🗑&lt;/button&gt;</code> → name is \"Delete\" (aria-labelledby wins over the emoji text).</li><li><code>&lt;label for=\"e\"&gt;Email&lt;/label&gt;&lt;input id=\"e\"&gt;</code> → input's name is \"Email\".</li></ul>","teach":"<p>At its core, accname is just <strong>a tie-breaker</strong>. An element can be labeled in five different ways at once, and a screen reader can only speak <em>one</em> name — so something has to decide which source wins. accname is that decision procedure, written down as a strict, ordered list.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Imagine a person with several name tags: a formal badge pinned on (aria-labelledby), a sticker they wrote themselves (aria-label), a nameplate on their desk (a native &lt;label&gt;), and the name printed on the document they're holding (text content). When the receptionist announces them, she follows a fixed rule: read the pinned badge if there is one; otherwise the self-written sticker; otherwise the desk nameplate; otherwise whatever the document says. She never reads all four — she reads the highest-priority one present.</div><p>The order matters because it's about <em>authorial intent</em>. <code>aria-labelledby</code> and <code>aria-label</code> sit at the top because a developer who adds them is explicitly overriding everything else — they're saying \"ignore the visible text, the real label is this.\" Below that come the host-language mechanisms HTML already provides: a <code>&lt;label for&gt;</code> tied to an input, the <code>alt</code> of an image, a fieldset's <code>&lt;legend&gt;</code>, a table's <code>&lt;caption&gt;</code>. Only if none of those exist does the browser fall back to the element's own text, and finally to the lowly <code>title</code> attribute.</p><p>Two traps fall out of this. First, <code>aria-label</code> silently <em>replaces</em> visible text — so <code>&lt;button aria-label=\"Submit\"&gt;Cancel&lt;/button&gt;</code> looks like Cancel but is announced as Submit, a real and common bug. Second, accname concatenates: an <code>aria-labelledby</code> that points at several IDs joins their text in order, which is how you build composite names from existing on-screen text without duplicating strings.</p><div class=\"key\">accname is the precedence ladder for an element's spoken name: aria-labelledby → aria-label → native labeling → text content → title. The first rung that yields text wins, and it's what fills the 'name' field of the accessibility tree that UIA hands to the screen reader.</div>","related":["uia"]},
  "cjk": {"term":"CJK","group":"FE-A11Y","aliases":["Chinese, Japanese, and Korean","CJKV","Chinese Japanese Korean"],"eli5":"A shorthand for the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean writing systems, which share large character sets and need IME text input.","memory":"CJK = Chinese, Japanese, Korean: the three languages whose huge character sets are typed via an IME.","full":"<p><strong>CJK</strong> stands for <em>Chinese, Japanese, and Korean</em> — a grouping used in software and typography because these languages share important characteristics: very large character repertoires (tens of thousands of Han characters / kanji / hanja), and the fact that users <em>compose</em> characters through an <strong>Input Method Editor (IME)</strong> rather than pressing one key per character. (A variant, <strong>CJKV</strong>, adds Vietnamese.)</p><p>The grouping became standard during the development of <strong>Unicode</strong>: to fit these scripts into a unified character set, Unicode performed <em>Han unification</em>, merging shared Chinese-origin characters used across the three languages into common code points. This work, ongoing since the early 1990s, is why \"CJK\" appears constantly in encoding, font, and text-handling contexts.</p><p>Its relevance to frontend is text input and rendering. Because CJK characters are typed by composing phonetic input into final characters via an IME, the browser fires <em>composition events</em> (<code>compositionstart</code>, <code>compositionupdate</code>, <code>compositionend</code>). The deck's UX guidance: for a search/autocomplete box, <strong>don't fire queries mid-composition</strong> for CJK input — listen for composition events so you only search once the user has committed the character, not on every intermediate keystroke.</p>","worked":"<p>Suppressing search while a CJK character is still being composed via the IME:</p><pre><code>const input = document.querySelector('#search')\nlet composing = false\n\ninput.addEventListener('compositionstart', () =&gt; { composing = true })\ninput.addEventListener('compositionend',  (e) =&gt; {\n  composing = false\n  runSearch(e.target.value)   // fire only after the char is committed\n})\n\ninput.addEventListener('input', (e) =&gt; {\n  if (composing) return       // skip mid-composition keystrokes (CJK)\n  runSearch(e.target.value)\n})</code></pre><p>Without the guard, typing one Japanese word could fire several useless searches on the intermediate romaji.</p>","teach":"<p>At its core, CJK is just a <strong>label for the three East Asian writing systems that don't map one-key-to-one-character</strong>. In English you press \"A\" and get \"A.\" But Chinese, Japanese, and Korean have thousands of characters — far more than a keyboard has keys — so users type phonetically and an <strong>IME (Input Method Editor)</strong> converts that input into the final character.</p><div class=\"analogy\">Imagine ordering at a counter where you can't point at one button per dish because there are 50,000 dishes. Instead you spell out the sounds of what you want, the clerk shows you a list of matching dishes, and you pick the right one — only <em>then</em> is your order final. The spelling-and-choosing is the IME's <strong>composition</strong> phase; the moment you confirm is <code>compositionend</code>. Acting on your half-spelled order would be a mistake.</div><p>This matters for any text field. When a user types Japanese, they might enter romaji like \"nihon,\" see candidate characters, and convert to 日本. During that in-between phase the input box technically contains intermediate text, and the browser fires <code>input</code> events for each keystroke. If your autocomplete naively searches on every <code>input</code> event, it fires several pointless, confusing queries on gibberish before the real word exists.</p><p>The fix is to watch the <strong>composition events</strong>: set a flag on <code>compositionstart</code>, ignore <code>input</code> events while that flag is true, and only run your search on <code>compositionend</code> when the character is committed. Beyond input, CJK also affects fonts (huge glyph sets, bigger font files), line-breaking rules, and vertical text — but the IME/composition gotcha is the one that bites interactive UIs most often.</p><div class=\"key\">The takeaway: <strong>CJK users compose characters through an IME, so don't treat every keystroke as final.</strong> Listen for composition events and act only on <code>compositionend</code>, or your search/autocomplete will fire on half-typed input.</div>","related":["i18n","l10n"]}
});
